[{"id":"TZO000001","type":"mcq","stimulusHtml":"<p class=\"dap_body\">Which of the following statements best describes the purpose of photographic portraits of African American leaders, like the one in Source 1? </p>","features":[{"type":"sharedpassage","html":"<div class=\"stimulus_reference\"><p class=\"dap_body\"><span aria-level=\"3\" class=\"selected-document-header\" role=\"heading\"><strong>Source 1</strong></span></p><figure class=\"image\" data-original-file-name=\"TZO000000_Stim 1_APC...\" style=\"padding-top:30px;\"><img alt=\"A black and white photographic portrait of Frederick Douglass. Douglass sits facing the camera with a serious expression on his face. He wears a suit, vest, and bow tie. The photograph is in a golden frame.\" data-filename=\"\" data-height=\"850\" data-image-id=\"\" data-sizeinkb=\"\" data-status=\"\" data-uploadedon=\"\" data-width=\"718\" height=\"auto\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/578/TZO000000_Stim_1_APC___.png\" style=\"aspect-ratio:718/850;\" width=\"718\"/><figcaption>Photographic Portrait of Frederick Douglass, Taken Shortly After His Return to the United States from Great Britain, Circa 1850</figcaption></figure><p class=\"dap_copyright\"><span style=\"background-color:#ffffff;color:#1e1e1e;\">National Portrait Gallery, Smithsonian Institution</span></p> <p class=\"dap_body\"> </p><p class=\"dap_body\"><span aria-level=\"3\" class=\"selected-document-header\" role=\"heading\"><strong>Source 2</strong></span></p><figure class=\"image\" data-original-file-name=\"TZO000000_Stim 2_APC...\" style=\"padding-top:30px;\"><img alt=\"A quilted portrait of Harriet Tubman titled I Go to Prepare a Place for You. Tubman is shown in an elegant dress made of brightly colored fabrics. She is seated and facing the viewer with a serious expression on her face. Her face and hands are depicted using fabrics of various bright colors. The background is composed of dark purple and bright blue flowers.\" data-filename=\"\" data-height=\"850\" data-image-id=\"\" data-sizeinkb=\"\" data-status=\"\" data-uploadedon=\"\" data-width=\"676\" height=\"auto\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/578/TZO000000_Stim_2_APC___.png\" style=\"aspect-ratio:676/850;\" width=\"676\"/><figcaption>Bisa Butler, African American Artist, <i>I Go to Prepare a Place for You,</i> 2021 Quilted Portrait of Harriet Tubman, Based on an 1868 Photograph of Tubman</figcaption></figure><p class=\"dap_copyright\">© Bisa Butler. Collection of the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture, purchased through the American Women’s History Initiative Acquisitions Pool, administered by the Smithsonian American Women’s History Initiative</p></div>"}],"choicesHtml":["<p class=\"dap_body\">They were used by enslavers to help track and return African Americans who had escaped from slavery.</p>","<p class=\"dap_body\">They aimed to refute stereotypes about Black people by showing them as dignified and respectable.</p>","<p class=\"dap_body\">They were used by visual artists to demonstrate the technological superiority of photography over painting.</p>","<p class=\"dap_body\">They were used by emigrationists to persuade African Americans that they can build better lives for themselves in Africa.</p>"],"answer":"1710135647270.6816"}]